{{Otheruses|仏教における水瓶|生活用水を蓄える水瓶|甕}} '''水瓶'''（すいびょう、みずがめ）は、[[仏教]]において[[閼伽]]（水）を入れる[[瓶]]で、[[比丘]]（びく）が持たなければならない18種類の持ち物のひとつ。[[サンスクリット語]]の「グンディ」の訳で、'''軍持'''（ぐんじ）と音訳される。仏像のうち[[観音菩薩]]などの[[持物]]とされることもある。
水瓶は、古くから使われ陶器のほか鋳銅製などがあり、[[文化財]]に指定されているものもある。
== 関連項目 == * [[瓶]] * [[花瓶]] * [[みずがめ座]] * [[宝瓶宮]]
{{buddhism2}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:すいひよう}} [[category:仏像]] [[Category:容器]] [[Category:工芸]] {{buddhism-stub}}

{{Otheruses|Water Bottles in Buddhism|Water storage jars for daily use|甕}}
[[File:荒久遺跡出土 灰釉花文浄瓶.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Gray Glazed Floral Patterned Water Jar<br/>{{small|Excavated from Araku Site (Ichihara City, Chiba Prefecture). Displayed at Ichihara History Museum.}}]]
'''Water Jar''' (水瓶, ''suibyō'' or ''mizugame'') is a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] vessel used to hold [[argha]] (holy water). It is one of the 18 essential possessions that a [[bhikshu]] (monk) must carry. The Sanskrit term "kundī" is translated as '''Gunji''' (軍持) in phonetic transcription. In Buddhist iconography, it is sometimes depicted as an attribute held by deities such as [[Avalokiteśvara]] (Kannon Bodhisattva).

Water jars have been in use since ancient times and can be made of pottery, cast bronze, or other materials. Some examples are designated as [[Cultural Properties]].
== See Also ==
* [[Jar]]
* [[Vase]]
* [[Aquarius (constellation)]]
* [[Aquarian Age]]

